Personalized Reading Recommendations from a Book Dataset¶

This is a book recommendation system which recommends 5 books based on your taste and preference. The dataset holds variety of information about a book for instance, its ratings, authors, publishers and more. Some of these information are typically used in order to determine the taste of a user and make appropriate personaized reading recommendations.

Task - 1 : Performing EDA(Exploratory Data Analysis on book data)¶

About the data:¶

The data consist comprehensive list of books listed in goodreads. It consist typically 12 columns (bookID, title, authors, average_rating, isbn, isbn13, language_code, num_pages , ratings_count, text_reviews_count, publication_date, publisher)

Why EDA?¶

EDA facilitates the identification of missing values, outliers, and inconsistencies in the data, enabling data cleaning and preprocessing tasks. It also helps in formulating research questions, refining hypotheses, and selecting appropriate modeling techniques for further analysis. By uncovering patterns and insights, EDA provides a foundation for making informed decisions and guiding subsequent data-driven investigations or predictive modeling tasks.

Observation:¶

Authors, title, average_rating, num_pages, and publisher are the most informative features since they give an idea of the user's behavior. For example: if a person reads JK Rowling's books, we can identify details from its metadata which include the number of pages, average ratings, publisher, and language. This data helps us to recommend similar titles to the use, based on any of the above features.¶

For example: If the user reads Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix, we know that the author is JK Rowling and its average rating is 4.49 and the number of page is 870 and the language is English. Hence, with this data, we can recommend books by similar author, ratings, and publisher.¶

b) TF-IDF scores are calculated¶

TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) is a numerical representation used to assess the importance of a term within the data. It calculates a weight for each term based on its frequency within the data.¶

TF-IDF is useful because it helps prioritize terms that are both frequently occurring within a document and relatively rare across the entire corpus. By assigning higher weights to these terms, TF-IDF emphasizes their significance in distinguishing documents from one another¶

In [67]:
#Finding the tf-idf score of each row value against the entire column of the specified column. 
vectorizer1 = TfidfVectorizer()
author_tfidf = vectorizer1.fit_transform(data['authors'])

vectorizer2 = TfidfVectorizer()
publisher_tfidf = vectorizer2.fit_transform(data['publisher'])

vectorizer3 = TfidfVectorizer()
title_tfidf = vectorizer3.fit_transform(data['title'])

c) Making a data frame of the TF-IDF n dimension array of each token. The columns of this data frame are the feature names of the vectorizer. Which is the token name itself.¶

In [68]:
#Making a dataframe of tf-idf of each token
authorscoredf = pd.DataFrame(author_tfidf.toarray(),columns = vectorizer1.get_feature_names_out())
publisherscoredf = pd.DataFrame(publisher_tfidf.toarray(),columns = vectorizer2.get_feature_names_out())
titlescoredf = pd.DataFrame(title_tfidf.toarray(),columns = vectorizer3.get_feature_names_out())

d) Along with the columns, we are finding the sum of the tf-idf score of individual tokens in each row which gives us a combined score for each row.¶

In [69]:
#Sum of tf-idf score 
df_main['author_tfidf']=authorscoredf.sum(axis=1)
df_main['publisher_tfidf']=publisherscoredf.sum(axis=1)
df_main['title_tfidf']=titlescoredf.sum(axis=1)

f) Fetching the information that the user entered and performing a transformation on it. Similar steps are followed with the information given by the user. Including Finding the tf-idf score, making a dataframe of each token and finding the sum of scores to be compared against author and title.¶

This is done because the transformation which is done with reference data should be done with the user input data as well. (Cannot do cosine similarity on a string)¶

Will match the index of the top 5 cosine distances with the dataframe to get the actual recommendations.¶

When the user will enter the information, it will be converted into a score. Then that score will be compared with final_df.¶

In [73]:
#final_df and df_main are here just for comparision and getting the recommendations against the user input value

def get_recommendations(authors, title, finaldf, df_main):
    #Converting string into dataframe
    data = {'authors':[authors], 'title':[title]}
    newdf = pd.DataFrame(data)
    
    #Finding the tf-idf score of each row value against the entire column of the specified column. 
    vectorizer4 = TfidfVectorizer()
    authornew_tfidf = vectorizer4.fit_transform(newdf['authors'])
    vectorizer5 = TfidfVectorizer()
    titlenew_tfidf = vectorizer5.fit_transform(newdf['title'])
    
    #Making a dataframe of tf-idf of each token
    authornewscoredf = pd.DataFrame(authornew_tfidf.toarray(),columns = vectorizer4.get_feature_names_out())
    titlenewscoredf = pd.DataFrame(titlenew_tfidf.toarray(),columns = vectorizer5.get_feature_names_out())
    
    #Sum of tf-idf score 
    newdf['authornew_tfidf']=authornewscoredf.sum(axis=1)
    newdf['titlenew_tfidf']=titlenewscoredf.sum(axis=1)
    
    #Dropping the existing columns from df_main
    finaldf1 = newdf.drop(columns = ['authors','title'])
    
    #Comparing it with author and title 
    cos_sim = cosine_similarity(finaldf[['author_tfidf','title_tfidf']],finaldf1)
    
    #Then storing it in a df
    cosine_sim_df = pd.DataFrame(cos_sim)

    #Get top 5 rows with highest cosine similarity scores
    top_5_rows = cosine_sim_df.stack().nlargest(5).reset_index()
    top_5_rows.columns = ['row1', 'row2', 'similarity']

    #Get text values of top 5 rows 
    top_5_text = df_main.iloc[top_5_rows['row1'].values][['title','authors']].values
    
    #Returning the top 5 rows with similarity
    return top_5_text, top_5_rows['similarity']
